            <div type="translation">
                <p>Jesus Christ, Son of God, conquers. The light of Christ shines for all. The discovery (of the cross) was given from God to Helena.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Good condition. The victorious acclamation Ἰ(ησοῦ)ς Χ(ριστὸ)ς Nικᾷ with the combination of Υἱ(ὸ)ς Θ(εο)ῦ usually appears on either side and in-between the arms of a patriarchal cross and it is very common in the byzantine painted churches. The connection of the acclamation to Constantine recalls his Vision of the Cross with the words τούτῳ νίκα before the Milvian bridge battle. The tetragram-acronym EEEE in the lower corners of the cross, glorifies the discovery of the True Cross by Constantine’s mother and can be interprete in many different ways.</p>
            </div>
